Global energy consumption is increasing day by day due to industrial and high population growth. There is a major global challenge in striving to meet the future energy demand in renewable, sustainability, clean, and safe energy sources1,2. One way in improving the electricity demand is by scavenging waste heat using thermoelectric generators3. The conversion of waste heat into electricity will provide alternative energy that will reduce our dependence on fossil fuels and reduce greenhouse gas emissions4. The performance of thermoelectric energy conversion devices depends on thermoelectric figure of merit ZT (Eq. 1), where S, σ, κtotal = κe + κl, and T are the Seebeck coefficient, electrical conductivity, total thermal conductivity, and absolute temperature, respectively5. Thermal conductivity comes from two sources: (1) electrons and holes transporting heat κe and (2) phonons travelling through the lattice κl6.1ZT=S2σktotal\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
